<!-- 
development location for this file:
 http://sclpandevo/devo-do-not-publish/marilynprojects/lightreading/06_07/
staging location for this file:
 http://sclpandevo/light/publications/lightreading/06_07/
live location for this file:
 http://www.seattle.gov/light/publications/lightreading/06_07/ 
 
Here's what usually happens:

 1. Add the color scheme to the style sheet, and choose which style goes with which article's title, putting just the titles into the web pages without the article text. (use the PDF file for comparison.
 2.  Load in the raw images to the web page draft.  One change that can be done right away is to change the title graphic to include the image that's in the PDF version.  This usually takes resizing the title graphic down and adding the image to its right.
  3 Let Marilyn know that the page is ready for her to add the text of the articles and code the HTML for wach article's text.  She usually also changes the image tags to render the images the size she would really like them.
   4 When Marilyn's done, we take the images and resize them for real to the basic dimensions she's used in the img tags.
   5 Use something like the code validator in HomeSite and check the code of the page.
   6 When it's all done, make a copy of the whole directory to the staging area
       http://sclpandevo/light/publications/lightreading/06_07/
      Send this link to Larry and Marilyn for final review.  Any edits that are needed, make sure the copies stay in synch - I usually edit Marilyn's copy as the real source, then promote to staging to keep everything flowing in the right direction.

   7 After final content and code and graphics QA, it's Son's turn.
             a-  Son promotes the folder minus devo-do-not-publish to the live site  and tests to make sure all the files got there and the links still work (and they don't have anything like "sclpandevo" in any of them and such things).  
              http://www.seattle.gov/light/publications/lightreading/06_07/
                          
             b- He adds a link to the "Publications" section of the SCLPAN database, checks with everyone to make sure the database is okay to roll, then promotes it.

  8  Almost done!  Send a success message to everyone, and this is when Larry goes to work
             -  Larry adds new links on the SCL PAN and SCL InWeb home pages to the new issue of Light Reading.

  9 Finally, someone goes to the City Light News Web Board and posts and notice to the customers who've signed up to be notified about Light Reading that the latest issue is available.  This person is sure to include links to other very cool stuff on Seattle.gov...     -->

